et not only explores the lives of those at the top but also sheds light on how extreme inequality comes to seem ordinary and acceptable to the rest of us.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aRich peoplezUnited States. 0aSocial classeszUnited States. 0aSocial stratificationzUnited States. 0aWealthzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Classes & Economic Disparity.2bisacsh1 aSherman, Rachel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691195162zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691195162423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691195162/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles